<p>Much of Lincolnâ€™s advertisement campaign is supposed to be funny, so laugh all you want to, but McConaugheyâ€™s final lines in â€œBalanceâ€ resonate as a steadfast truth â€” as something to live by. He says: â€œYou gotta find that balance, where taking care of yourself takes care of more than just yourself.â€ Iâ€™ll admit, I laugh every time I hear him say that because of the way he delivers the final â€œyourself.â€ I laugh because it sounds as if McConaughey was put behind the seat of a Lincoln, and behind Refnâ€™s cameras, without a script; it sounds as if heâ€™s making this stuff up. I think thatâ€™s where the truth behind what Lincoln is selling to us lies. None of us have a script to read from. Lincoln seems to be saying, <em>We get that. So where is forward for you? Where is forward for all of us?</em></p>

<p>Although each commercial is complete unto itself, their succession from â€œIntroâ€ to â€œBalanceâ€ depicts McConaughey as a wandering man, struggling toward the realization of a personal and social epiphany. â€œBalanceâ€ is the realization of his epiphany. In a way, it is an epiphany for all of us.</p>

<p>Lincoln is an American automotive industry. Through its commercials, it is speaking directly to Americans, as well as to the people in the markets that it wants to establish abroad. It wants to sell us an American narrative, but Americans, as well as the rest of the world, have grown weary of that narrative, for important intellectual and emotional reasons;Â so Lincoln has disguised that narrative.</p>

<p>Consider again McConaugheyâ€™s monologue from the first commercial, â€œIntro.â€ He says, â€œI know there are those who say you canâ€™t go back. Yes, you can. You just have to look in the right place.â€ Compare this to Barrack Obamaâ€™s slogan in the 2008 Presidential Election: â€œYes we can.â€Â  In 2008, Obama told America that we can go forward. Â The collective is always composed by the individual. Individual responsibility produces collective progress. The way forward is always two steps forward, and one step back, on and on and on.Â  But to tell you that flat-out in our age of irony and simulacra sounds either cliche, pretentious or naive. Â Behind the style, behind the verbosity,Â Lincoln is selling you America. Are you buying?</p>

